// Hoff's 4-bit architecture concept
// 
// CPU (4004): 4-bit ALU, 16 registers, 3-level stack
// ROM (4001): 256 bytes program storage
// RAM (4002): 40 nibbles data storage
// I/O (4003): Keyboard/display interface
// 
// 4 chips instead of 12
// Same hardware, different software = different products

// 4004 Specifications (Final)
// 
// Transistors: 2,300
// Die size: 3mm √ó 4mm (12 mm¬≤)
// Process: 10 micron
// Clock speed: 740 kHz
// Instructions: 46
// Registers: 16 √ó 4-bit
// Stack: 3 levels
// Performance: 92,000 ops/sec

// 4-bit ALU operations
// 
// ADD: A + B + Carry
// SUB: A + ~B + 1 (two's complement)
// AND: A & B
// OR:  A | B
// XOR: A ^ B
// 
// BCD correction:
// If result > 9, add 6 to wrap to next digit
// Example: 7 + 5 = 12 ‚Üí add 6 ‚Üí 18 (carry 1, digit 8)

// First Silicon Testing Process
// 
// 1. Wafer probe: test chips before cutting
// 2. Basic functions: clock, reset, power
// 3. Instruction tests: does ADD work?
// 4. Integration tests: run real programs
// 5. Speed tests: timing margins OK?
// 
// If any fail ‚Üí redesign ‚Üí 6-8 weeks lost

